[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] The following simple program demonstrates Go's concurrency features to implement an asynchronous program.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] It launches two lightweight threads ("goroutines"): one waits for the user to type some text, while the other implements a timeout.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] The select statement waits for either of these goroutines to send a message to the main routine, and acts on the first message to arrive (example adapted from David Chisnall's book).
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] The testing package provides support for automated testing of go packages.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] It is possible to run tests in parallel.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] The net/http package provides support for creating web applications.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] This example would show "Hello world!" when localhost:8080 is visited.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] Go has found widespread adoption in various domains due to its robust standard library and ease of use.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] The interface system, and the deliberate omission of inheritance, were praised by Michele Simionato, who likened these characteristics to those of Standard ML, calling it "a shame that no popular language has followed [this] particular route".
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] By June 2015, its ranking had dropped to below 50th in the index, placing it lower than COBOL and Fortran.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] But as of January 2017, its ranking had surged to 13th, indicating significant growth in popularity and adoption.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] Go was again awarded TIOBE Programming Language of the Year in 2016.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] The evaluation got a rebuttal from the Go development team.
[src:gin-gonic/go-programming-language] On November 10, 2009, the day of the general release of the language, Francis McCabe, developer of the Go! programming language (note the exclamation point), requested a name change of Google's language to prevent confusion with his language, which he had spent 10 years developing.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware often enables interoperability between applications that run on different operating systems, by supplying services so the application can exchange data in a standards-based way.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware sits "in the middle" between application software that may be working on different operating systems.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] It is similar to the middle layer of a three-tier single system architecture, except that it is stretched across multiple systems or applications.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Examples include EAI software, telecommunications software, transaction monitors, and messaging-and-queueing software.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] The distinction between operating system and middleware functionality is, to some extent, arbitrary.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] While core kernel functionality can only be provided by the operating system itself, some functionality previously provided by separately sold middleware is now integrated in operating systems.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] A typical example is the TCP/IP stack for telecommunications, nowadays included virtually in every operating system.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware is defined as software that provides a link between separate software applications.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] It is sometimes referred to as plumbing because it connects two applications and passes data between them.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware allows data contained in one database to be accessed through another.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] This makes it particularly useful for enterprise application integration and data integration tasks.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] It also facilitated distributed processing, the connection of multiple applications to create a larger application, usually over a network.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] when compared to the operating system and network services.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware offers some unique technological advantages for business and industry.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] For example, traditional database systems are usually deployed in closed environments where users access the system only via a restricted network or intranet (e.g., an enterprise’s internal network).
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] With the phenomenal growth of the World Wide Web, users can access virtually any database for which they have proper access rights from anywhere in the world.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware addresses the problem of varying levels of interoperability among different database structures.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware facilitates transparent access to legacy database management systems (DBMSs) or applications via a web server without regard to database-specific characteristics.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Businesses frequently use middleware applications to link information from departmental databases, such as payroll, sales, and accounting, or databases housed in multiple geographic locations.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] In the highly competitive healthcare community, laboratories make extensive use of middleware applications for data mining, laboratory information system (LIS) backup, and to combine systems during hospital mergers.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware helps bridge the gap between separate LISs in a newly formed healthcare network following a hospital buyout.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware can help software developers avoid having to write application programming interfaces (API) for every control program, by serving as an independent programming interface for their applications.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] For Future Internet network operation through traffic monitoring in multi-domain scenarios, using mediator tools (middleware) is a powerful help since they allow operators, searchers and service providers to supervise Quality of service and analyse eventual failures in telecommunication services.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Finally, e-commerce uses middleware to assist in handling rapid and secure transactions over many different types of computer environments.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] In short, middleware has become a critical element across a broad range of industries, thanks to its ability to bring together resources across dissimilar networks or computing platforms.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] In 2004 members of the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) carried out a study of Middleware with respect to system integration in broadcast environments.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] This involved system design engineering experts from 10 major European broadcasters working over a 12-month period to understand the effect of predominantly software-based products to media production and broadcasting system design techniques.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] The resulting reports Tech 3300 and Tech 3300s were published and are freely available from the EBU web site.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Message-oriented middleware (MOM) is middleware where transactions or event notifications are delivered between disparate systems or components by way of messages, often via an enterprise messaging system.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] With MOM, messages sent to the client are collected and stored until they are acted upon, while the client continues with other processing.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] software may queue, duplicate, translate and deliver messages to disparate systems or components in a messaging system.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Intelligent Middleware (IMW) provides real-time intelligence and event management through intelligent agents.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] The IMW manages the real-time processing of high volume sensor signals and turns these signals into intelligent and actionable business information.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] The actionable information is then delivered in end-user power dashboards to individual users or is pushed to systems within or outside the enterprise.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] It is able to support various heterogeneous types of hardware and software and provides an API for interfacing with external systems.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] It should have a highly scalable, distributed architecture which embeds intelligence throughout the network to transform raw data systematically into actionable and relevant knowledge.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] It can also be packaged with tools to view and manage operations and build advanced network applications most effectively.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Content-centric middleware offers a simple *provider-consumer* abstraction through which applications can issue requests for uniquely identified content, without worrying about where or how it is obtained.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Juno is one example, which allows applications to generate content requests associated with high-level delivery requirements.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] The middleware then adapts the underlying delivery to access the content from sources that are best suited to matching the requirements.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] This is therefore similar to Publish/subscribe middleware, as well as the Content-centric networking paradigm.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware enables a client to use services running on remote systems.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware, it is possible for applications to send objects and request services in an object-oriented system.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] is middleware between applications and database servers.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] integration interface that operates between embedded applications, the embedded operating system, and external applications.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliance is a generic term referring to any form of middleware that manages policy rules.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] They can mediate between data owners or producers, data aggregators, and data users.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Among heterogeneous institutional systems or networks they may be used to enforce, reconcile, and monitor agreed information management policies and laws across systems (or between jurisdictions) with divergent information policies or needs.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliances support policy-based information management processes by enabling rules-based processing, selective disclosure, and accountability and oversight.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] IBM, Red Hat, Oracle Corporation and Microsoft are some of the vendors that provide middleware software.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Vendors such as Axway, SAP, TIBCO, Informatica, Objective Interface Systems, Pervasive, ScaleOut Software and webMethods were specifically founded to provide more niche middleware solutions.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Groups such as the Apache Software Foundation, OpenSAF, the ObjectWeb Consortium (now OW2) and OASIS' AMQP encourage the development of open source middleware.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Microsoft .NET "Framework" architecture is essentially "Middleware" with typical middleware functions distributed between the various products, with most inter-computer interaction by industry standards, open APIs or RAND software licence.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] Solace provides middleware in purpose-built hardware for implementations that may experience scale.
[src:gin-gonic/middleware-distributed-applications] StormMQ provides Message Oriented Middleware as a service.
[src:gin-gonic/page] Gin is a high-performance HTTP web framework written in Go.
[src:gin-gonic/page] It provides a Martini-like API but with significantly better performance—up to 40 times faster—thanks to httprouter.
[src:gin-gonic/page] Gin is designed for building REST APIs, web applications, and microservices where speed and developer productivity are essential.
[src:gin-gonic/page] Gin has a rich ecosystem of middleware for common web development needs.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In packet switching networks, routing is the higher-level decision-making that directs network packets from their source toward their destination through intermediate network nodes by specific packet forwarding mechanisms.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Packet forwarding is the transit of network packets from one network interface to another.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Intermediate nodes are typically network hardware devices such as routers, gateways, firewalls, or switches.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] General-purpose computers also forward packets and perform routing, although they have no specially optimized hardware for the task.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The routing process usually directs forwarding on the basis of routing tables.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Routing tables maintain a record of the routes to various network destinations.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Routing tables may be specified by an administrator, learned by observing network traffic or built with the assistance of routing protocols.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Routing, in a narrower sense of the term, often refers to IP routing and is contrasted with bridging.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] IP routing assumes that network addresses are structured and that similar addresses imply proximity within the network.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Structured addresses allow a single routing table entry to represent the route to a group of devices.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In large networks, structured addressing (routing, in the narrow sense) outperforms unstructured addressing (bridging).
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Routing has become the dominant form of addressing on the Internet.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Bridging is still widely used within local area networks.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Unicast is the dominant form of message delivery on the Internet.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This article focuses on unicast routing algorithms.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] With static routing, small networks may use manually configured routing tables.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Larger networks have complex topologies that can change rapidly, making the manual construction of routing tables unfeasible.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Nevertheless, most of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) uses pre-computed routing tables, with fallback routes if the most direct route becomes blocked (see routing in the PSTN).
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Dynamic routing attempts to solve this problem by constructing routing tables automatically, based on information carried by routing protocols, allowing the network to act nearly autonomously in avoiding network failures and blockages.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Examples of dynamic-routing protocols and algorithms include Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Distance vector algorithms use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This approach assigns a *cost* number to each of the links between each node in the network.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Nodes send information from point A to point B via the path that results in the lowest *total cost* (i.e., the sum of the costs of the links between the nodes used).
[src:gin-gonic/routing] When a node first starts, it only knows of its immediate neighbors and the direct cost involved in reaching them.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The neighboring nodes examine this information and compare it to what they already know; anything that represents an improvement on what they already have, they insert in their own table.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Over time, all the nodes in the network discover the best next hop and total cost for all destinations.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] When a network node goes down, any nodes that used it as their next hop discard the entry and convey the updated routing information to all adjacent nodes, which in turn repeat the process.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Eventually, all the nodes in the network receive the updates and discover new paths to all the destinations that do not involve the down node.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] When applying link-state algorithms, a graphical map of the network is the fundamental data used for each node.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] To produce its map, each node floods the entire network with information about the other nodes it can connect to.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Each node then independently assembles this information into a map.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Using this map, each router independently determines the least-cost path from itself to every other node using a standard shortest paths algorithm such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The result is a tree graph rooted at the current node, such that the path through the tree from the root to any other node is the least-cost path to that node.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This tree then serves to construct the routing table, which specifies the best next hop to get from the current node to any other node.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] A link-state routing algorithm optimized for mobile ad hoc networks is the optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:gin-gonic/routing] OLSR is proactive; it uses Hello and Topology Control (TC) messages to discover and disseminate link-state information through the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Using Hello messages, each node discovers 2-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:gin-gonic/routing] MPRs distinguish OLSR from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Distance vector and link-state routing are both intra-domain routing protocols.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] They are used inside an autonomous system, but not between autonomous systems.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Both of these routing protocols become intractable in large networks and cannot be used in inter-domain routing.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Distance vector routing is subject to instability if there are more than a few hops in the domain.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Link-state routing needs significant resources to calculate routing tables.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] It also creates heavy traffic due to flooding.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Path-vector routing is used for inter-domain routing.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] It is similar to distance vector routing.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Path-vector routing assumes that one node (there can be many) in each autonomous system acts on behalf of the entire autonomous system.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This node is called the *speaker node.* The speaker node creates a routing table and advertises it to neighboring speaker nodes in neighboring autonomous systems.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The idea is the same as distance vector routing, except that only speaker nodes in each autonomous system can communicate with each other.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The speaker node advertises the path, not the metric, of the nodes in its autonomous system or other autonomous systems.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The path-vector routing algorithm is similar to the distance vector algorithm in the sense that each border router advertises the destinations it can reach to its neighboring router.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] However, instead of advertising networks in terms of a destination and the distance to that destination, networks are advertised as destination addresses and path descriptions to reach those destinations.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The path, expressed in terms of the domains (or confederations) traversed so far, is carried in a special path attribute that records the sequence of routing domains through which the reachability information has passed.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] A route is defined as a pairing between a destination and the attributes of the path to that destination, thus the name, path-vector routing.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The routers receive a vector that contains paths to a set of destinations.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Path selection involves applying a routing metric to multiple routes to select (or predict) the best route.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Most routing algorithms use only one network path at a time.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Multipath routing and specifically equal-cost multi-path routing techniques enable the use of multiple alternative paths.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In computer networking, the metric is computed by a routing algorithm, and can cover information such as bandwidth, network delay, hop count, path cost, load, maximum transmission unit, reliability, and communication cost.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The routing table stores only the best possible routes, while link-state or topological databases may store all other information as well.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] *Metric*: When comparing routes learned via the same routing protocol, a lower metric is preferred.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Metrics cannot be compared between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] *Administrative distance*: When comparing route table entries from different sources, such as different routing protocols and static configuration, a lower administrative distance indicates a more reliable source and thus a preferred route.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Because a routing metric is specific to a given routing protocol, multi-protocol routers must use some external heuristic to select between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Cisco routers, for example, attribute a value known as the administrative distance to each route, where smaller administrative distances indicate routes learned from a protocol assumed to be more reliable.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] A local administrator can set up host-specific routes that provide more control over network usage, permit testing, and better overall security.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This is useful for debugging network connections or routing tables.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In some small systems, a single central device decides ahead of time the complete path of every packet.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In some other small systems, whichever edge device injects a packet into the network decides ahead of time the complete path of that particular packet.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In either case, the route-planning device needs to know a lot of information about what devices are connected to the network and how they are connected to each other.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Once it has this information, it can use an algorithm such as A* search algorithm to find the best path.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In high-speed systems, there are so many packets transmitted every second that it is infeasible for a single device to calculate the complete path for each and every packet.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Early high-speed systems dealt with this with circuit switching by setting up a path once for the first packet between some source and some destination; later packets between that same source and that same destination continue to follow the same path without recalculating until the circuit teardown.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Later high-speed systems inject packets into the network without any one device ever calculating a complete path for packets.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In large systems, there are so many connections between devices, and those connections change so frequently, that it is infeasible for any one device to even know how all the devices are connected to each other, much less calculate a complete path through them.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Such systems generally use next-hop routing.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Most systems use a deterministic dynamic routing algorithm.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] When a device chooses a path to a particular final destination, that device always chooses the same path to that destination until it receives information that makes it think some other path is better.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] A few routing algorithms do not use a deterministic algorithm to find the best link for a packet to get from its original source to its final destination.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Instead, to avoid congestion hot spots in packet systems, a few algorithms use a randomized algorithm—Valiant's paradigm—that routes a path to a randomly picked intermediate destination, and from there to its true final destination.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In many early telephone switches, a randomizer was often used to select the start of a path through a multistage switching fabric.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Depending on the application for which path selection is performed, different metrics can be used.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] For example, for web requests, one can use minimum latency paths to minimize web page load time, or for bulk data transfers, one can choose the least utilized path to balance load across the network and increase throughput.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] A popular path selection objective is to reduce the average completion times of traffic flows and the total network bandwidth consumption.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Recently, a path selection metric was proposed that computes the total number of bytes scheduled on the edges per path as a selection metric.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] An empirical analysis of several path selection metrics, including this new proposal, has been made available.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In some networks, routing is complicated by the fact that no single entity is responsible for selecting paths; instead, multiple entities are involved in selecting paths or even parts of a single path.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Complications or inefficiency can result if these entities choose paths to optimize their own objectives, which may conflict with the objectives of other participants.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] A classic example involves traffic in a road system, in which each driver picks a path that minimizes their travel time.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] With such routing, the equilibrium routes can be longer than optimal for all drivers.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In particular, Braess's paradox shows that adding a new road can *lengthen* travel times for all drivers.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In a single-agent model used, for example, for routing automated guided vehicles (AGVs) on a terminal, reservations are made for each vehicle to prevent simultaneous use of the same part of an infrastructure.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This approach is also referred to as context-aware routing.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The Internet is partitioned into autonomous systems (ASs) such as internet service providers (ISPs), each of which controls routes involving its network.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] First, AS-level paths are selected via the BGP protocol that produces a sequence of ASs through which packets flow.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Each AS may have multiple paths, offered by neighboring ASs, from which to choose.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] These routing decisions often correlate with business relationships with these neighboring ASs, which may be unrelated to path quality or latency.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Second, once an AS-level path has been selected, there are often multiple corresponding router-level paths to choose from.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This is due, in part, because two ISPs may be connected through multiple connections.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In choosing the single router-level path, it is common practice for each ISP to employ hot-potato routing: sending traffic along the path that minimizes the distance through the ISP's own network—even if that path lengthens the total distance to the destination.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] For example, consider two ISPs, *A* and *B*.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Each has a presence in New York, connected by a fast link with latency 5 ms—and each has a presence in London connected by a 5 ms link.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Suppose both ISPs have trans-Atlantic links that connect their two networks, but *A*'s link has latency 100 ms and *B*'s has latency 120 ms.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] When routing a message from a source in *A*'s London network to a destination in *B*'s New York network, *A* may choose to immediately send the message to *B* in London.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This saves *A* the work of sending it along an expensive trans-Atlantic link, but causes the message to experience latency 125 ms when the other route would have been 20 ms faster.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Additionally, a similar routing challenge can be observed in cellular networks, where different packets are destined for various endpoints, and each link exhibits varying spectral efficiency.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In this context, the selection of the *optimal* path involves considering latency and packet error rate.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] To address this, multiple independent entities, one for each base station, play a crucial role in path selection while striving to optimize overall network performance.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] A 2003 measurement study of Internet routes found that, between pairs of neighboring ISPs, more than 30% of paths have inflated latency due to hot-potato routing, with 5% of paths being delayed by at least 12 ms.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Inflation due to AS-level path selection, while substantial, was attributed primarily to BGP's lack of a mechanism to directly optimize for latency, rather than to selfish routing policies.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] It was also suggested that, were an appropriate mechanism in place, ISPs would be willing to cooperate to reduce latency rather than use hot-potato routing.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Such a mechanism was later published by the same authors, first for the case of two ISPs and then for the global case.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] As the Internet and IP networks have become mission critical business tools, there has been increased interest in techniques and methods to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation, flapping or downtime.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Monitoring routing in a network is achieved using route analytics tools and techniques.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] In networks where a logically centralized control is available over the forwarding state, for example, using software-defined networking, routing techniques can be used that aim to optimize global and network-wide performance metrics.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] This has been used by large internet companies that operate many data centers in different geographical locations attached using private optical links, examples of which include Microsoft's Global WAN, Facebook's Express Backbone, and Google's B4.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Global performance metrics to optimize include maximizing network utilization, minimizing traffic flow completion times, maximizing the traffic delivered prior to specific deadlines and reducing the completion times of flows.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] Work on the later over private WAN discusses modeling routing as a graph optimization problem by pushing all the queuing to the end-points.
[src:gin-gonic/routing] The authors also propose a heuristic to solve the problem efficiently while sacrificing negligible performance.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:gin-gonic/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
